The '''eye–hand span''' is the distance across part of a text, usually a linguistic text that is being copied via typing or a piece of [[Music notation|notated music]] that is being performed, defined as the distance between the position of the [[human eye|eye]]s acquiring that information and the [[hand]](s) typing or performing it.<ref>{{cite book |last=Land |first=Michael F. |last2=Tatler |first2=Benjamin W. |title=Looking and Acting |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |year=2009 |page=67 |isbn=978-0-19-857094-3 }}</ref> Specifically, the eye–hand span is typically measured from the location of [[Fovea centralis|central visual input]], and stretches between the [[syllable]] or [[Chord (music)|chord]] currently being typed or performed, and the lateral location of the simultaneous fixation.  This distance may be measured either in units of linear measurement or in characters or other "bits" of data.  Some authors refer to the eye–hand span as the "perceptual span" for the visual information perceivable around the region of center of vision used in reading,<ref>{{cite book|author=Keith Rayner|title=Eye Movements in Reading: Perceptual and Language Processes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lx51Brw60cMC&pg=PA81|year=2012|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-323-14628-9|page=81}}</ref> and in some cases including [[peripheral vision|peripheral input]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Keith |last=Rayner |first2=Alexander |last2=Pollatsek |title=Eye Movements, the Eye-Hand Span, and the Perceptual Span during Sight-Reading of Music |journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science |volume=6 |issue=2 |year=1997 |pages=49–53 [p. 49] |jstor=20182443 |doi=10.1111/1467-8721.ep11512647}}</ref> The eye–hand span is analogous to the eye–voice span in [[Reading (process)|reading]] [[language]] aloud and in [[singing]].

