{{For|another sequencing process of same name|Oligotyping (sequencing)}}
'''Oligotyping''' is a [[diagnosis|diagnostic]] or [[molecular biology|molecular biological]] method for classification of [[organism]]s by short intervals of primary [[DNA sequence]].  

Oligotyping 'systems' are sets of recognized target sequences which identify the members of the categories within the classification.  The classification may be for the purpose of primary biological [[taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]], or for a functional classification.  

==Classifying bacteria==
Oligotyping has been used for classifying [[bacteria]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roring|first=S|last2=Brittain|first2=D|last3=Bunschoten|first3=A. E|last4=Hughes|first4=M. S|last5=Skuce|first5=R. A|last6=van Embden|first6=J. D. A|last7=Neill|first7=S. D|date=1998-03-15|title=Spacer oligotyping of Mycobacterium bovis isolates compared to typing by restriction fragment length polymorphism using PGRS, DR and IS6110 probes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378113598001783|journal=Veterinary Microbiology|volume=61|issue=1–2|pages=111–120|doi=10.1016/S0378-1135(98)00178-3}}</ref> identifying bacterial antibiotic resistance genes,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mabilat|first=C.|last2=Courvalin|first2=P.|date=1990-11-01|title=Development of "oligotyping" for characterization and molecular epidemiology of TEM beta-lactamases in members of the family Enterobacteriaceae.|url=http://aac.asm.org/content/34/11/2210|journal=Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy|language=en|volume=34|issue=11|pages=2210–2216|doi=10.1128/AAC.34.11.2210|issn=0066-4804|pmid=2073111|pmc=172024}}</ref> identifying genetic factors in human infectious disease,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rani|first=Rajni|last2=Fernandez-Vina|first2=M. A.|last3=Zaheer|first3=S. A.|last4=Beena|first4=K. R.|last5=Stastny|first5=Peter|date=1993-07-01|title=Study of HLA class II alleles by PCR oligotyping in leprosy patients from North India|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1399-0039.1993.tb02179.x/abstract|journal=Tissue Antigens|language=en|volume=42|issue=1|pages=133–137|doi=10.1111/j.1399-0039.1993.tb02179.x|issn=1399-0039|pmid=8284786}}</ref> and performing histocompatibility tests for human blood or bone marrow donors/recipients .

